This pattern lets us dynamically add behaviour to individual objects without changing other objects of the same class.
It uses decorator classes to wrap concrete components, making functionality more flexible and reusable.
Wraps existing objects using decorator classes to add new behaviour at runtime.
Extends functionality without modifying original code, following the OCP.

Ex:
1.Coffee shop: A coffee is enhanced with add on like milk, sugar, or whipped cream.
2.video streaming platforms: Videos can be wrapped with decorators for subtitles, audios or language options

Components:
Both decorator and components classes have is-a and has-a relationship.
1.Component Interface: Defines common operations for components and decorators.(Decorator inherits from Component).
2.Concrete Component: Core object with basic funcationality 
3.Decorator: Abstract wrapper that holds component reference and adds behaviour.
4.Concrete Decorator: Specific decorators that extend functionality of the component.

Working:
Define component interface that both core object and decorators implement.
Create a concrete component that implements the interface.
Create decorator classes that also implement the interface and have a refernce to a common object.
Decorator classes add or override behaviour by delegating to the wrapped object